final_answer("In C, there is no direct support for containers like vector and set, so we'll need to use an array and manually keep track of the elements.

```c
#include<stdio.h>
#include<stdlib.h>
#define MAX_SIZE 100

int* remove_duplicates(int* numbers, int size, int* resultSize) {
    int* result = malloc(sizeof(int)*MAX_SIZE);
    int i, j, flag;

    *resultSize = 0;
    for (i = 0; i < size; i++){
        flag = 0;
        for (j = 0; j < *resultSize; j++){
            if(numbers[i] == result[j]){
                flag = 1;
                break;
            }
        }
        if(flag == 0){
            result[(*resultSize)++] = numbers[i];
        }
    }

    return result;
}

int main() {
    int input[] = {1, 2, 3, 2, 4, 2, 5, 6, 7, 8, 9};
    int resultSize = 0;
    int* result = remove_duplicates(input, sizeof(input)/sizeof(input[0]), &resultSize);

    for (int i = 0; i < resultSize; i++) {
        printf("%d ", result[i]);
    }
    free(result);
    return 0;
}
```

Here, we have some restrictions compared to the original C++ code. First off, we're assuming that the array is not going to have more than 100 unique elements (defined by `MAX_SIZE`). Keep in mind that this might not work for large arrays due to the 2 nested for loops, which makes it have a time complexity of O(n^2). 

Remember to always free the memory allocated with `malloc` in C to avoid memory leaks.")
</code>

