final_answer("Abstract Class in Java:

An abstract class in Java is a class that cannot be instantiated, meaning you cannot create new instances of an abstract class. It works as a base class for other classes. The abstract class's methods can run with default code, or they can be declared abstract and done by its subclasses.

Example (Animal.java):
```java
public abstract class Animal {
    private String name;

    public Animal(String name) {
        this.name = name;
    }

    public abstract void eat();

    public abstract void speak();

    public String getName() {
        return name;
    }
}
```
Benefits of Abstract Class in Java:

Abstract classes allow you to declare fields that type-check at compile-time, ensuring that a class meets a specific contract. They can provide a default behavior and is used to share among several closely related classes (Ex: `getName()` method in the Animal class).

Interfaces vs Abstract Classes in Java:

Interfaces are used primarily to enforce that certain methods are implemented in the classes. Starting from Java 8, interfaces can contain implemented methods, static methods, and default methods. However, an interface does not have any state, it may have final static variables though. It can be used to achieve full abstraction and multiple inheritance in Java.

On the other hand, an abstract class can also have constants and method implementation. In addition to that, it can have fields and constructors. While the abstract class is used to provide a base for closely related objects (is-a relationship), interfaces are better for defining capabilities (can-do relationship) across unrelated classes.")
</code>

