final_answer("Yes, a user can implement such a requirement for their custom class by making use of `std::enable_if` along with `std::is_same` or `std::is_convertible` type traits to restrict the deduction guide to a particular class or type.

Example implementation:

```cpp
#include <string>
#include <type_traits>

template<typename CharT, typename Traits = std::char_traits<CharT>>
class MyString {
public:
    using size_type = std::size_t;
    // Rest of the class implementation
};

template <typename CharT, typename Traits,
          typename = std::enable_if_t<std::is_same_v<typename MyString<CharT, Traits>::size_type, std::size_t>>>
MyString(const CharT*, typename MyString<CharT, Traits>::size_type) -> MyString<CharT, Traits>;
```

In this example, `std::enable_if` ensures the deduction guide is only active if `MyString::size_type` is `std::size_t`. Generally, you can refer to aliases of the deduced type by using the scope operator (`::`) to access nested types inside the class templates within the deduction guide declaration. `std::enable_if_t` is a helper that simplifies this by avoiding the explicit `typename ... ::type` syntax.")
