<code>
final_answer("Generally, properties in C# are actually syntactic sugar over methods. A getter behaves like a method with no parameters, and a setter behaves like a method with one parameter. Therefore, getters and setters can be viewed as special types of function delegates, meaning you can treat them like method delegates.

Here's an example of how you might use delegates to access a property getter or to set a property using its setter:

```csharp
class MyClass
{
    public string MyProperty { get; set; }
}

delegate object GetterDelegate<T>(T t);
delegate void SetterDelegate<T, V>(T t, V value);

void GetProperty<T, RET>(T obj, GetterDelegate<T> getter)
{
    RET ret = (RET)getter.Invoke(obj);
    Console.WriteLine(ret);
}

void SetProperty<T, V>(T obj, V value, SetterDelegate<T, V> setter)
{
    setter.Invoke(obj, value);
}

static void Main(string[] args)
{
    MyClass myObj = new MyClass { MyProperty = "" };

    // setting property value
    SetProperty<MyClass, string>(myObj, "Hello, World!", (o, v) => o.MyProperty = v);

    // getting property value
    GetProperty<MyClass, string>(myObj, o => o.MyProperty);

    Console.ReadLine();
}
```
In this example, I'm using two delegates, `GetterDelegate<T>` and `SetterDelegate<T, V>`. The `GetterDelegate<T>` takes an object and returns a value, while the `SetterDelegate<T, V>` takes an object and a value, and returns void.")
